  <data name="AboutContractors" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>A Contractor usually bids on larger multi-trade projects such as Kitchens, Baths, Additions, etc. They usually have some employees, but also assign specialty work to Subcontractors and Independent Contractors who bring their skills in on a temporary basis for the project at hand. Contractors usually deal directly with Homeowners and commercial building managers. Contractors usually have a commercial office address and/or a showroom.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="AboutContractorsLbl" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>About Contractors</value>
  </data>
  <data name="AboutHomeowners" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>A Homeowner is a residential home owner or commercial building manager that hires Contractors for multi-trade projects, or Subcontractors for specialized skills (i.e. an electrician), and/or Independent Contractors for general Handyman tasks that do not require a separate skilled trade license.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="AboutIndependentcontractorsDTL" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>An Independent Contractor usually works alone or with 1 helper. They usually work on smaller jobs, one at a time, for Homeowners and Contractors. Independent Contractors usually work from home. They do assembly projects, (i.e. assemble furniture or a grill), and other small jobs around a home or business. Most Handyman work is done by Independent Contractors. Many Independent Contractors work as an employee for a larger company, and do the small jobs as a side gig in the evenings and on weekends.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="AboutSubcontractors" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>A Subcontractor usually offers services in 1, 2, or more particular trades. They obtain work from Contractors who need their specialized license and skills to complete larger more complex building or remodeling projects. Some Subcontractors obtain work directly from Homeowners and commercial building managers. For example: A Heating and Cooling company might work directly for a Homeowner to install a new replacement furnace, and also work as a Subcontractor installing furnaces for a builder of new homes. Subcontractors may have a commercial office address or work from home (depending on their company size).</value>
  </data>
